
[1]pan

   PAN, n.

   1. A vessel broad and somewhat hollow or depressed in the middle, or
   with a raised border; used for setting milk and other domestic
   purposes.

   2. The part of a gun-lock or other fire-arms which holds the priming
   that communicates with the charge.

   3. Something hollow; as the brain pan.

   4. Among farmers, the hard stratum of earth that lies below the soil;
   called the hard pan.

   5. The top of the head.

               PAN, v.t. To join; to close together. [Local.]
